  "prompt": "How often do a Tesla's batteries need to be replaced?",
  "response": "Tesla vehicles are designed with long-lasting lithium-ion batteries that typically require replacement only after a significant amount of use or degradation. Here are some key points regarding Tesla battery lifespan and replacement:\n\n1. **Battery Longevity**: Tesla batteries are engineered to last a very long time. Most Tesla vehicles are expected to retain 70-90% of their battery capacity after **200,000 to 300,000 miles** (320,000 to 480,000 kilometers), depending on usage, maintenance, and environmental factors.\n\n2. **Degradation Rate**: Battery degradation is most noticeable in the first few years of ownership, leveling off over time. On average, Tesla batteries lose about **1-2% of their range per year**, but this can vary based on driving habits, charging patterns, and climate.\n\n3. **Replacement Need**: Many Tesla owners may never need to replace their batteries. Tesla's warranty typically covers the battery for **8 years or 100,000 to 150,000 miles** (model-dependent), guaranteeing a minimum of 70% battery capacity retention during that period. Replacement is usually only necessary if there's a significant drop in performance or a malfunction.\n\n4. **Cost of Replacement**: If a replacement is needed outside the warranty period, the cost can range from **$10,000 to $20,000+**, depending on the model and battery size. However, advancements in battery technology and declining costs may reduce this expense over time.\n\n5. **Factors Affecting Battery Life**: To maximize battery lifespan, Tesla recommends avoiding frequent full charges, using scheduled charging, and minimizing exposure to extreme temperatures.\n\nIn summary, Tesla batteries are highly durable and rarely need replacement under normal conditions. Most drivers will enjoy their Tesla's original battery for the majority of the vehicle's lifespan.",
